            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a lively and energetic 9-year-old boy who typically enjoys playing soccer with his neighborhood friends after school, collecting trading cards, and watching animated adventure shows on weekends. He lives with his mother, father, and 6-year-old sister in a suburban household. He attends third grade at a local elementary school and is described by his teachers as curious and sociable. His mother reports that he is generally a healthy child who loves eating at outdoor school events and trying new foods.\n\nApproximately three days ago, {patientName} began experiencing sudden-onset watery diarrhea, occurring up to 6–8 times per day, accompanied by crampy, periumbilical abdominal pain. His mother noticed he was unusually fatigued and had lost his appetite entirely. The illness began about 24 hours after {patientName} attended a school picnic where he consumed potato salad, grilled chicken, and lemonade that had been left out in warm weather for several hours.\n\nOn presentation, {patientName} appears pale and mildly lethargic, with dry lips and slightly sunken eyes suggesting mild-to-moderate dehydration. He is intermittently wincing due to abdominal cramps and has been reluctant to eat or drink since symptoms began. His mother also reports one episode of low-grade fever (38.2°C) and a single episode of vomiting on the first day of illness. He denies blood in stool but reports stools are loose, watery, and foul-smelling.\n\nAt home, {patientName} enjoys outdoor play in the garden, visits to the local swimming pool during summer, and participating in weekend soccer tournaments. His diet is generally balanced but includes occasional fast food. The family has not traveled internationally in the past year, and no other household members have been ill, though two of his classmates reportedly have similar symptoms following the same picnic event."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:000d9537-3766-49f7-8797-7bbbc53b822e",
